               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-1016" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1016" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1016" type="surname" value="ARNOLD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-1016" type="given" value="CHARLES JAMES"></interp>CHARLES JAMES ARNOLD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am ship-keeper of the schooner <hi rend="italic">Bailard</hi>, which was lying in the East and West India Docks. On the 22nd of March I lost a three-step ladder, which I had seen safe on the deck at three o'clock that day—I asked the prisoner who was mate of the <hi rend="italic">Provi<lb></lb>dence</hi>, which was lying alongside of the schooner, if he had got my ladder—he said, no—on the Thursday following I got an officer, aud went with him on board the Providence—I saw the ladder found on board the Provi<lb></lb>dence aft the pump-well—it belonged to Messrs. Foster and Smith, African merchants, and owners of the schooner—the captain's name if Henry William Dring.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you the charge of the schooner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—tbe captain was out of the vessel—a vessel called the <hi rend="italic">Sea Witch</hi> was lying astern of the <hi rend="italic">Providence</hi>—have heard that the persons on board that vessel bad stolen the ladder belonging to the Provi<lb></lb>dence—tbe prisoner said that as they had taken his ladder, he had taken mine—he would derive no advantage from the ladder, it was for the use of the ship.</p>
